# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-pollution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The **1948 Donora smog**, also called the **Donora death fog**, was an air pollution disaster that occurred in Donora, Pennsylvania, beginning on October 27, 1948, and lasting several days.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] It was caused by hydrogen fluoride and sulfur dioxide emissions from U.S.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Steel's Donora Zinc Works and its American Steel & Wire plant during an atmospheric temperature inversion.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] It killed 20 people and caused respiratory problems for 6,000 of the 14,000 people living in Donora, a mill town on the Monongahela River 24 miles (39 km) southeast of Pittsburgh.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The event is commemorated by the Donora Smog Museum.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Sixty years later, the incident was described by *The New York Times* as "one of the worst air pollution disasters in the nation's history." Even 10 years after the incident, mortality rates in Donora were significantly higher than those in other communities nearby.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Hydrogen fluoride and sulfur dioxide emissions from U.S.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Steel's Donora Zinc Works and its American Steel & Wire plant were frequent occurrences in Donora.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] What made the 1948 event more severe was a temperature inversion, a situation in which warmer air aloft traps pollution in a layer of colder air near the surface.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The pollutants in the air mixed with fog to form a thick, yellowish, acrid smog that hung over Donora for five days.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The sulfuric acid, nitrogen dioxide, fluorine, and other poisonous gases that usually dispersed into the atmosphere were caught in the inversion and accumulated until rain ended the weather pattern.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The fog started building up in Donora on Wednesday, October 27, 1948.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] By the following day it was causing coughing and other signs of respiratory distress for many residents of the community in the Monongahela River valley.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Many of the illnesses and deaths were initially attributed to asthma.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The smog continued until it rained on Sunday, October 31, by which time 20 residents of Donora had died and approximately one third to one half of the town's population of 14,000 residents had been sickened.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Another 50 residents died of respiratory causes within a month after the incident.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Two of the heroes to emerge during the four-day smog were Chief John Volk of the Donora Fire Department and his assistant Russell Davis.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Volk and Davis responded to calls from Friday night, the 29th until Sunday night, the 31st, depleting their supply of 800 cubic feet (23 m3) of oxygen, borrowing more from all nearby municipalities, including McKeesport, Monessen, and Charleroi.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The eight doctors in the town, who belonged to the Donora Medical Association, made house calls much like the firefighters during the period of intense smog, often visiting the houses of patients who were treated by the other doctors in town.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] This was a result of patients calling every doctor in town in the hope of getting treatment faster.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] It was not until mid-day Saturday, the 30th, that Mrs.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Cora Vernon, executive director of the American Red Cross, had it set up so that all calls going to the doctors’ offices would be switched to the emergency center being established in the town hall.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The smog was so intense that driving was nearly abandoned; those who chose to continue driving took risks. “I drove on the left side of the street with my head out the window.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Steering by scraping the curb.” recalled Davis.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] It was not until Sunday morning, the 31st, that a meeting occurred between the operators of the plants and the town officials.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Chambon, the burgess (mayor) of Donora, requested the plants temporarily cease operations.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Westhaver, said the plants had already begun shutting down operation at around 6:00 that morning.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] With the rain alleviating the smog, the plants resumed normal operation the following morning.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Researchers analyzing the event have focused likely blame on pollutants from the zinc plant, whose emissions had killed almost all vegetation within a half-mile radius of the plant.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Davis, director of the Center for Environmental Oncology at the University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute, has pointed to autopsy results showing fluorine levels in victims in the lethal range, as much as 20 times higher than normal.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Fluorine gas generated in the zinc smelting process became trapped by the stagnant air and was the primary cause of the deaths.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Further research was conducted by Mary Amdur about the effects of the smog; she was pressured to withdraw publication of these results but refused to bow.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Preliminary results of a study performed by Clarence A.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Mills of the University of Cincinnati and released in December 1948 showed that thousands more Donora residents could have been killed if the smog had lasted any longer than it had.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Steel, which never acknowledged responsibility for the incident, calling it "an act of God".
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] While the steel company did not accept blame, it reached a settlement in 1951 in which it paid about $235,000, which was stretched over the 80 victims who had participated in the lawsuit, leaving them little after legal expenses were factored in.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] By 1949, a year after the disaster, the total value of the predominantly residential property in Donora had declined by nearly 10%.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The Donora Smog was one of the incidents where Americans recognized that exposure to large amounts of pollution in a short period of time can result in injuries and fatalities.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The incident was little spoken of in Donora until a historical marker was placed in the town in 1998, to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the incident.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The 60th anniversary, in 2008, was commemorated with memorials for the families of the victims and other educational programs.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The Donora Smog Museum was opened on October 20, 2008, located in an old storefront at 595 McKean Avenue near Sixth Street, with the slogan "Clean Air Started Here".
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Fewer than 6,000 people still live in Donora.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The Donora event led to the first large-scale epidemiological investigation of an environmental health disaster in the United States.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] An account of the smog was published in 1950 by the noted medical writer Berton Roueché in *The New Yorker* under the title "The Fog".
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Together with another article, "A Pig From Jersey" (about a mass-case of foodborne illness), this article won him the 1950 Albert Lasker Medical Journalism Award.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] "The Fog" was later included in his celebrated collection of short stories *Eleven Blue Men*.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] Devra Davis' 2002 novel *When Smoke Ran Like Water* starts with the Donora Smog.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The 2009 novel *Don't Kill the Messenger* by Joel Pierson features a fictional town, Wyandotte, Pennsylvania, which became a ghost town after a smog incident, based on the Donora Smog.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] In 2023 Andy McPhee's book, *Donora Death Fog: Clean Air and the Tragedy of a Pennsylvania Mill Town*, was published by the University of Pittsburgh Press.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] An hour-long documentary, *Rumor of Blue Sky*, produced by Andrew Maietta and Janet Whitney, aired on WQED TV in April 2009.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The film features archival images and interviews with survivors of the environmental tragedy.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The Donora smog incident was mentioned in Netflix's *The Crown* in 2016, when it depicted a similar incident in London in 1952.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The Weather Channel produced an episode of *When Weather Changed History* on the Donora smog incident.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The incident would be revisited in a later Weather Channel series, *Weather That Changed The World*.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] The 2024 podcast "Cement City", about two journalists who live for three years in Donora, includes extensive discussion of the smog incident in episode 1.
[src:air-pollution/1948-donora-smog] In 1995, the Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission installed a historical marker noting the historic importance of the event.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] The **1982 Bukit Merah radioactive pollution** is a radioactive waste pollution incident in Bukit Merah of Kinta District in Central Perak, Malaysia.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] The outcome of the pollution case took several years to complete with no acknowledgement of responsibilities from companies involved despite the closure of factory in 1994 that become the source of pollution.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] Translated Excerpt from Consumer Association.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] In 1982, the newly established company began extracting yttrium from a mineral named monazite which contains rare-earth elements and the radioactive elements thorium and uranium.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] Since the ARE started its operation, residents from a nearby town of Papan began to complain of an unpleasant odour and smoke from the factory where they also had reported breathing difficulties as a result of the pollution.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] The residents later discovered in 1984 that the extracting company of ARE had built a waste channel to a disposal site near their town under the consent of the state government of Perak.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] Despite the conclusion gathered from international experts, the government decided to proceed with the activities where the residents later continue their protests and performed a one-day hunger strike against the government decision.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] In 1985, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Musa Hitam showed his concern by visiting the site and subsequent cabinet meeting led by the latter was held to move the disposal site to the Kledang Range, about 5 kilometres from the town area.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] Following the third revelation, the federal government through a minister from the Prime Minister's Office Kasitah Gaddam said the levels were still safe despite it being more than the limit, with the excuse of the number of sites being very small.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] To prove that their claims were indeed true, the residents of Papan aided by residents from the nearby towns of Bukit Merah, Lahat, Menglembu and Taman Badri Shah formed the Bukit Merah Acting Committee.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] Another expert from Japan was called thereafter to gather further evidence where he found that the radiation levels were 800 times the permitted maximum level.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] In 1985, eight of the town residents including one who is a cancer victim brought the case to the High Court with 1,500 people from the affected area present to hear the verdict.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] A temporary stop work order was subsequently issued by the court until satisfactory safety measures were taken by the ARE company.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] However, in just a month after the order, the company invited an American atomic specialist to prove the factory is safe to continue its operation.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] The company was then ordered by the court to stop all operations but the AELB still issued a license to the company to continue their operations in 1987.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] With the company's refusal to stop despite the court order, the affected residents began to sue the company which evolved into a court battle that lasted 32 months and in July 1992, the residents won their case against the company with the court ordering them to close their factory within 14 days.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] With Mitsubishi's intervention and further international pressure, the company finally stopped their operations despite having won the court battle locally.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] Mitsubishi Chemical reached an out-of-court settlement with the affected residents by agreeing to donate $164,000 to the community's schools while denying any responsibility for the related illnesses from pollution caused by the ARE related works.
[src:air-pollution/1982-bukit-merah-radioactive-pollution] After the 1982 Bukit Merah radioactive pollution incident, the mine in Malaysia was the focus of a US$100 million cleanup that proceeded in 2011.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] The **1997 group of forest fires in Indonesia** that lasted well into 1998 were probably among the two or three, if not the largest, forest fires group in the last two centuries of recorded history.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] In the middle of 1997 forest fires burning in Indonesia began to affect neighbouring countries, spreading thick clouds of smoke and haze to Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] Then Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad searched desperately for a solution, and based on a plan by the head of the Malaysian fire and rescue department sent a team of Malaysian firefighters across to Indonesia under code name Operation Haze.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] This is to mitigate the effect of the Haze to Malaysia economy.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] The value of the Haze damage to Malaysian GDP is estimated to be 0.30 per cent.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] Seasonal rains in early December brought a brief respite but soon after the dry conditions and fires returned.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] By late 1997 and early 1998 Brunei, Thailand, Vietnam, the Philippines and Sri Lanka had also felt the haze from the smoke of the forest fires.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] By the time the 1997–98 forest fires were finally over some 8 million hectares of land had burned while countless millions of people suffered from air pollution.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] The 1997 Indonesian forest fires were caused by changing land use which made the tropical forest vulnerable to fire during a drought associated with that year's El Niño.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] Indonesian forests have historically been resistant to burning even during long dry seasons and despite the use of fire to clear land for swidden agriculture.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] The land use changes that led to the fires were a combination of industrial-scale logging, draining peatlands for conversion to oil palm and fast-growing tree plantations, and a massive government program to drain swamps and convert them to rice paddies.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] A total of 240 people perished in the wildfires.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] Due to the heavy smoke caused by the fires, an Airbus A300 operating as Garuda Indonesia Flight 152 crashed on approach to Medan's Polonia Airport.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] All 234 people on board died, making it the worst crash in Indonesian history.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] The total economic value of the damages is conservatively estimated to be US$4.47 billion, of which by far the largest share was borne by Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] This figure excludes a number of damages that are especially difficult to measure or to value in monetary terms, such as loss of human life, long-term health impacts, and some biodiversity losses.
[src:air-pollution/1997-indonesian-forest-fires] Forest fires in Indonesia in 1997 were estimated to have released between 0.81 and 2.57 gigatonnes of carbon into the atmosphere, which is between 13 and 40% of the annual carbon dioxide emissions from burning fossil fuels.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] The **1997 Southeast Asian haze** was an international air pollution disaster that occurred during the second half of 1997, its after-effects causing widespread atmospheric visibility and health problems within Southeast Asia.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Considered the most severe Southeast Asian haze event of all time, the total costs of the 1997 haze are estimated at US$9 billion, due mainly to health care and disruption of air travel and business activities.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] The influence of the 1997 fires in Kalimantan and Sumatra on ambient air quality was evident by July and peaked in September/October before weakening by November, when the delayed monsoonal rain extinguished the fires and improved air quality within the region.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] During the peak episode, satellite imagery (NASA/TOMS aerosol index maps) showed a haze layer that expanded over an area of more than 3,000,000 km2 (1,200,000 sq mi), covering large parts of Sumatra and Kalimantan.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Its northward extension partially reached Malaysia, Singapore, Brunei, Thailand and the Philippines and its westward extension reached Sri Lanka.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] During this period, particulate matter concentrations frequently exceeded national ambient air quality standards.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Monthly mean horizontal visibility at most locations in Sumatra and Kalimantan in September was below 1 km (0.62 mi) and daily maximum visibility was frequently below 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] The 1997 Southeast Asian haze was caused mainly by slash-and-burn techniques adopted by farmers in Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Slash and burn has been extensively used for many years as the cheapest and easiest means to clear the lands for traditional agriculture.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Fire is also used during the long fallow rotation of the so-called jungle rubber in Sumatra and Kalimantan to remove most of the biomass, including the woody parts before new plantations are re-established.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Fire may also be deliberately used as a weapon to claim property on the islands and provinces where land ownership is not clear, an action taken by both smallholders and large operators alike.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] After burning out its previous owner, the smallholder or large operator plants their own crops there, gaining de facto control over the disputed land .
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] During the dry season, dry fuels readily ignite and lead to large wildfires, and due to the 1997–98 El Niño event, the dry season in Southeast Asia was even drier than normal.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] These accidental fires may have the same underlying socio-economic and institutional problems.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] In cases like this, fire suppression can be very difficult and costly especially when they reach the highly flammable peat-swamp areas.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Atmospheric particulate matter was the form of air pollutant that predominantly contributed to the haze and degradation in ambient air quality standards during this crisis.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] In all countries affected by the smoke haze, an increase of acute health outcomes was observed.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Health effects; included emergency room visits due to respiratory symptoms such as asthma, upper respiratory infection, decreased lung function as well as eye and skin irritation, were caused mainly by this particulate matter.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] In Singapore, for instance, health surveillance showed a 30% increase in hospital attendance due to air quality related symptoms.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Generally, children and the elderly, as well as those with pre-existing respiratory and cardiac diseases were the most susceptible to adverse health outcomes from the haze exposure.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] The smoke haze episode has added to the urban and industrial air pollution in Southeast Asia, causing it to reach alarming levels in many metropolitan areas.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] By scattering and absorbing light, the fire-related particulate also resulted in reduced visibility; impairing transportation by air, land and water and seriously affecting the economies of Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Among the economic sectors affected most were air, land and sea transportation, construction, tourism and agricultural industries.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] EEPSEA/WWF estimated the economic value of the damages caused by the 1997 fires and haze.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] They estimated one billion US$ from haze-related damages for Indonesia only.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] The damages to Malaysia and Singapore are figured at 0.4 billion US$.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Including the fire related damages, the total damages are estimated to amount to 4.5 billion US$.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] However, a variety of the damages such as decreased quality of life, loss of biodiversity and atmospheric impacts are difficult to establish.
[src:air-pollution/1997-southeast-asian-haze] Fire-related smoke haze episodes also reveal a social component: a large part of the population in Southeast Asia do not have the financial means to buy protective measures such as respiratory masks and air conditioning, nor are they able to refrain from outdoor work when air pollution is high.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] The **2005 Malaysian haze** was an air pollution crisis caused primarily by fires in neighbouring Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] In August 2005, haze spread across Malaysia from forest fires on the Indonesian island of Sumatra, leading to air quality reaching hazardous levels in certain states and the capital city, Kuala Lumpur.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] The Malaysian government declared states of emergency in affected regions, closed schools and held crisis talks with Indonesian officials.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Farmers regularly burn scrub and forest to clear land during the dry season for agricultural purposes.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] The 2005 haze was at the time the worst to hit Malaysia since 1997.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] On 10 August 2005, air quality in the Malaysian capital city of Kuala Lumpur was so poor that health officials advised citizens to stay at home with doors closed.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Some schools were closed to keep children from being exposed to the haze.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] On 11 August 2005, a state of emergency was announced for the world's 12th largest port, Port Klang and the district of Kuala Selangor after air pollution there reached dangerous levels (defined as a value greater than 500 on the Air Pollution Index or API).
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] This was the first time the state of emergency had been imposed in Malaysia since the September 1997 haze, when Sarawak was placed in a state of emergency due to similar reasons.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] The state of emergency in the two affected areas meant that schools, government officials, the port, and offices were closed.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Shops carrying necessities, however, such as supermarkets and pharmacies remained open.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] After the API levels dropped to acceptable levels, the state of emergency was lifted on 13 August.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] By 13 August 2005, air quality and visibility returned to normal in Kuala Lumpur, as the haze moved northwards to the states of Perlis, Kedah and Penang, according to the Department of Environment's (JAS) API reading.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] On 16 August, air quality throughout Malaysia had returned to normal according to JAS statistics, as the haze was blown further northwards into Thailand.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Kuala Lumpur International Airport was unaffected during the hazy period but flights for non-ILS equipped planes from Subang airport were suspended until conditions cleared on 13 August.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Cloud seeding operations using RMAF C-130s were used throughout Malaysia, although the haze had moved north of Malaysia into Thailand and Cambodia.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Malaysia's Environment Minister, Adenan Satem, and Commodities Minister, Peter Chin, met with Indonesia's forestry minister and officials from its environment ministry in Medan.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Malaysia had sent 125 firefighters while Australia had sent 12 bushfire experts to fight Indonesia's estimated more than a thousand forest and scrub fires (estimate reached by counting hotspots greater than 1 km on satellite imagery, example of such an image shown below).
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Other nations pledged aid to Indonesia, including an offer from Singapore of planes for cloud seeding.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Japan, South Korea and Thailand also offered help.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] On 22 August, Malaysia extended its cloud seeding operations to include Indonesia, as requested by Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] The haze made a brief return on 11 September.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] The air pollutant index readings (API) were released for the first time by the Malaysian government since 1997.
[src:air-pollution/2005-malaysian-haze] Up to date readings are available for the 51 sites monitored automatically and continuously via the Department of Environment, Malaysia.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Air quality was lower, overall, for residents of more densely populated cities.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] In the highly urban and industrialised Klang Valley of Malaysia, in particular, the surrounding elevated terrain acted as a natural retainer of polluted air, aggravating the situation as the haze set in.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The haze was made worse than during previous occurrences by the El Niño-Southern Oscillation which delayed the year's monsoon season.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Fires in Kalimantan produce great amounts of smoke, burn a long time and are difficult to extinguish because they are on peatland, and once lit the fires can burn for months and release gases that produce sulphuric acid.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Air quality across the region appeared to improve in late October as heavy rainfall doused fires in Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Brunei, an independent sultanate that is surrounded by East Malaysia's Sarawak state on Borneo, had been affected by the haze from Kalimantan.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Rains brought some relief, and on 8 October, the Pollutant Standards Index had dropped to 46, which is within the "good" range.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] There was a brief spell of clear skies during the first week of Hari Raya, following a spell of rainy weather.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] But the haze returned on 31 October, with the Department of Environment, Parks and Recreation recording a PSI of 49.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The fires originated mostly in Kalimantan, the Indonesian part of Borneo, and on Sumatra, where they are set by swidden agriculturists employed by agroforestry concerns to clear land to grow pulp woods or market crops ahead of the growing season.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Satellite images taken over Borneo on 4 October revealed no less than 561 "hot spots" areas where fires had been set.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Officials in neighbouring countries accused Indonesian officials of doing nothing to stop the fires, though forestry ministry officials said they had firefighters “working” to douse the blazes on state-controlled land.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] However, they conceded that “most” of the fires were on private land.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Indonesia planned to deploy its military to aid fire fighting effort.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] To recruit more people to man the fire line, the government offered two days off for civil servants who volunteered for fire duty.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] But the country lacked adequate equipment for fighting forest fires, having aeroplanes that were far too small to carry enough water to douse the flames.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] In a bid to obtain bigger aircraft, the government leased two Beriev Be-200 aircraft from Russia, which are capable of skimming over water and taking on loads for sustained firefighting efforts.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The planes, which were flown and maintained by Russian crew, began operations on 1 November.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The fires forced schools to close, delayed and cancelled airline flights, disrupted shipping, and forced Indonesians to don face masks.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Cities affected include Pontianak, West Kalimantan, Palangkaraya, Central Kalimantan and Pekanbaru, Riau.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The haze was blamed for a Mandala Airlines flight from Balikpapan, the provincial capital of East Kalimantan, skidding off the runway upon landing at Tarakan on 3 October, when visibility was reported at around 400 metres.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] It has caused breathing problems for people in Riau and in Jambi Province.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On 21 October 12 airlines cancelled domestic flights from Soekarno-Hatta International Airport due to smog at many destinations, including Jambi, Banjarmasin, Jayapura, Semarang, Surabaya, Bengkulu, Denpasar, Makassar, Pekanbaru and Padang.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] A 20 October report by Malaysian government news agency BERNAMA offered a first-hand account of the scene in Kalimantan: "The suffocating smell of smoke, sore throat and eyes got worse when this reporter and a photographer stepped foot in central Kalimantan, forcing them to put on face masks.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Throughout the 200-kilometre journey from Banjarmasin to Palangkaraya, what could be seen of the forests on both sides of the road was a landscape of blackish soil with smoke still billowing from the ground in some areas and of withering trees and plants.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Local villagers, the report said, appeared to be unconcerned with the smog, saying it was "normal".
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] "If we do not burn the forest, where are we going to get our food from?" a villager said.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On the environmental front, fires destroyed 1 km2 of the Tesso Nilo National Park in Riau Province.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] At the Tanjung Puting National Park in Central Kalimantan, the haze adversely affected the orangutans.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The effects of the haze started in early July and affected the northern Malaysian states severely.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] However, the haze had cleared substantially throughout Peninsular Malaysia from 29 August 2006 due to the arrival of the rainy season.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The rain reduced the number of hotspots throughout Sumatra and the Malay Peninsula.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On 30 August 2006, *The Star* reported that Kuala Lumpur would be free of haze during the Independence Day.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] In the late evening just before midnight on 31 August 2006, the visibility in the Klang Valley was recorded to be very good.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Unfortunately, the haze returned again in late September when Muslim Malaysians were experiencing Ramadan.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] This was partly due to a change of wind direction towards the southwest, partially caused by Typhoon Xangsane.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The Sarawak state government had declared that schools would close if the API breaches the 300 mark.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The worst affected area in Peninsular Malaysia is Johor Bahru which recorded an API of 150 on 7 and 8 October.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] For now, many people are wearing masks to prevent themselves from inhaling excessive amounts of haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On 7 October, visibility in parts of East Malaysia fell to 300 metres.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On or about 9 October, the worst of the haze in Peninsular seemed to be in the state of Negeri Sembilan, where visibility in Sepang fell briefly to 500 metres and the API in Nilai reached 198, before the rain relieved the haze partially.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Shortly thereafter changing winds caused conditions to improve rapidly.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Sarawak has started cloud seeding attempts to try to encourage rainfall that will help relieve the haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Each cloud seeding session costs at least RM50,000 (roughly US$14,000).
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On 21 October, the winds has changed direction and started to blow the hazes away from Malaysia, and the following day, heavy rain has cleared the haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Later on 26 October, the heavy rain returned again, and there were isolated showers in Klang Valley.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The Star reported that the hazy days are soon coming to an end as the monsoon season is approaching.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] While the haze largely spared Singapore with 24-hour Pollutant Standards Index readings within the "Good" range for 15 days in September and the rest in the "Moderate" range and no higher than a reading of 66, its harmful effects became more prevalent in October.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On 7 October 2006, the 3-hour PSI reading breached the 100 mark at 8 a.m. and entered unhealthy levels for the first time in the year, as winds from neighbouring Sumatra blew the haze to Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] At 10 a.m., it hit 130, the highest in three years, before subsiding to 80 at 4 p.m. and climbing rapidly to 150 at 9 p.m., the worst since 1997, before ending the day at 136, still in the unhealthy range.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Although the air quality was set to improve with the arrival of the Northeast monsoon rains in mid-October, southeasterly winds extended the hazy season.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] A mild El Niño effect delayed the starting of the showers to late October or early November, or even until the end of November.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The prolonged haze could be attributed to the extended dry season, which put the rains on hold and affected wind patterns which brought the haze to Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Intermittent showers could occur in the pre-monsoon period, but these would do little in increasing air quality.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The unpredictable winds in the pre-monsoon period could bring haze from either Sumatra or Kalimantan.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Air quality remained in the moderate range for the next week until 14 October, when the 3-hour PSI readings gradually increased from 53 at 6 a.m. to peak at an unhealthy 116 at 10 p.m.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] This time, majority of the haze came from Kalimantan.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Similarly, on 15 October, the PSI readings increased from 69 at 6 a.m. to 98 at 3 p.m. and 4 p.m., 3 points short of reaching the unhealthy range.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] As winds remained southeasterly, haze from Kalimantan blew across the South China Sea to Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The next day, on 16 October, the PSI stayed in the 80s in the morning, before shooting up once again into the unhealthy range, hitting a high of 130 at 4 p.m. and 5 p.m.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The 3-hour PSI remained in unhealthy levels for 8 consecutive hours, between 2 p.m. and 9 p.m.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The haze obscured the sun, and symptoms of exposure to haze resurfaced in the general population.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The 24-hour PSI for 16 October reached 98, just 3 points short of unhealthy.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Visibility dropped to as low as 1 km in some areas, compared to the usual 20 km.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The PSI on 17 October gradually increased from the moderate range in the morning to slip into the unhealthy range at 4 p.m., reaching 106, before declining back to 100 in the moderate range at 10 p.m.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The hazy conditions were expected to persist.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] On 19 October, the PSI crept into the unhealthy range at 106 at 2 p.m., peaking at 113 at 4 p.m.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The National Environment Agency reported that the situation would not improve the next day.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Throughout the early morning on 20 October, the PSI kept in the 90s, before reaching a high of 103 at 8 a.m.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] This dropped to 74 by 7 p.m., although the PSI remained in the 90s in the afternoon.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Even though rain fell in some areas, this was not enough to "alleviate the haze situation".
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The NEA forecast thunderstorms over the weekend, but the southeasterly winds would continue to prevail.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The 24-hour PSI on 20 October also reached the unhealthy range at 102.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Later in October, though, the situation began to improve, with the PSI hitting a low of 11 at 2 p.m. on 26 October.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] However, in early November, intermonsoonal winds brought slight haze back to Singapore, with the 3-hour PSI in the moderate range most of the time.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The highest 3-hour average PSI recorded prior to that point 226 in September 1997.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] While some Singaporeans began donning face masks, others frequented shopping malls and public places like VivoCity, with many shopping before Deepavali at Little India, and going to Geylang Serai's annual Hari Raya bazaar.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Stallholders said that the haze had not affected their business.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] However, Singaporeans generally kept indoors, with some staying away from East Coast Park.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The government announced plans for a haze action plan if the situation became "extremely dangerous", which included priority treatment for haze-related illnesses.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Health Minister Khaw Boon Wan said that there was "very little that (could) be done to stop the haze", and advised people to remain indoors, especially those with prior respiratory conditions.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Some minor haze-related illness began to surface, but free clinics across the island did not report any increase in patients with this symptoms.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] However, attendance figures at polyclinics islandwide increased by 600 cases to about 15,000 cases of haze-related conditions in the first week of October as compared to the same period last month.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] This is despite the National Healthcare Group reporting that the number of people "complaining of the same ailments" has decreased from the same period last year.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Air purifier sales shot up during the hazy period.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Best Denki, an electronic store, sold S$350,000 worth of air purifiers and related items in 4 days, a 300 percent increase.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] However, experts from the Institute of Environmental Science & Engineering at the Nanyang Technological University said that only some of these products, like High Efficiency Particulate air filters, would effectively remove small particles from air.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Other kinds of air purifiers like ionizing purifiers gave off ozone which could cause symptoms similar to those caused by the haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The experts recommended regularly cleaning the filter media and opening windows to get some fresh air at night.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The western region, which includes Boon Lay, Choa Chu Kang and Jurong, seemed to be the "epicentre" of the haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Residents there complained of the worse conditions in their area, saying that it felt "hotter than usual", and health problems were more widespread.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The air quality levels in the west may have consistently been the worst, but only by several points.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Some speculated that the more polluted air was caused by the many construction sites and industrial parks in Jurong, but NEA refuted this, claiming that they did not contribute to the haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Polyclinics in Jurong and Bukit Batok had an increase of 20 percent admission for patients with respiratory problems and asthma.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Schools islandwide restricted outdoor activities and had to rethink post-examination activities and training or revert to wet-weather programmes.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The Singapore Sports School's swim team had to cut back on training when the haze reached unhealthy levels even though they were in the midst of various international competitions.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The Ministry of Education recommended that schools suspend all outdoor activities when the PSI reading passes 100, but some schools chose to move indoors regardless of the PSI.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Many Singaporean "fitness buffs" also made the move indoors.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Fitness clubs reported increases in turn-outs and check-ins, utilising gym facilities rather than outdoor activities.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Rock climbers were also affected, and began to move activities indoors instead.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The haze also caused increased sales and rental of entertainment VCD and DVD titles, but cinema attendance was unchanged.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The National Environment Agency website received about 170,000 hits on 14 October, as compared to the usual 60,000, and caused the server to temporarily go down due to the sheer volume of traffic.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] According to economists, Singapore suffered a US$50 million economic loss due to the onset of the haze in 2006.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] In July, the southern Thai provinces of Pattani and Satun suffered an on-and-off bout of smog, with the levels of pollutants in Satun being high enough to constitute a health hazard.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] In all, seven provinces were affected by the haze in July and August.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Haze was again reported on 6 October, with respiratory illnesses and eye irritation reported in Narathiwat.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Visibility and air quality were also affected in Songkhla, Satun and Yala.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Health warnings were issued and surgical masks were issued to residents.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Three days later, meteorological officials reported that the haze had thinned to almost normal visibility.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Strong winds in the region brought haze from Indonesia back into Songkhla, Satun, Pattani, Yala and Narathiwat provinces on 17 October.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Visibility in Yala and Songkhla was reduced to less than a kilometre, and officials warned fishermen going out to the Andaman Sea and Gulf of Thailand to "stay vigilant".
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Drivers were also asked to turn on their headlights.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Malaysia and Singapore criticised the way Indonesia handled the issue.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Both urged the latter to ratify the ASEAN Agreement on Transboundary Haze Pollution.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The Malaysian Environment Minister Azmi Khalid said "Frustration is an understatement", directed toward Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] There was also a protest in front of the Indonesia embassy in Kuala Lumpur, organised by local political parties.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Singaporean Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong expressed disappointment toward Indonesia soon after Azmi Khalid made his view public.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] In response to the letter, Indonesian President apologised for the regional haze.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Indonesia has earlier stated that it lacked the resources to combat the burning effectively.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Singapore proposed regional talks on the haze, to be held in Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] Indonesia, however, requested such talks to be held in Pekan Baru, Kalimantan instead.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] The request was agreed to and talks were held on 13 October 2006.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] At the meeting, Malaysia proposed the setting up of a regional fund to help combat the environmental disaster.
[src:air-pollution/2006-southeast-asian-haze] With the arrival of the northeastern winter monsoons in December, the haze problem was effectively ended for 2006.
[src:air-pollution/2009-southeast-asian-haze] The **2009 Southeast Asian haze** was an episode of large scale air pollution primarily caused by slash and burn practices used to clear land for agricultural purposes in Sumatra, Indonesia.
[src:air-pollution/2009-southeast-asian-haze] It affected the areas surrounding the Straits of Malacca which besides Indonesia include Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:air-pollution/2009-southeast-asian-haze] The haze began in early June 2009 and progressively became worse toward July.
[src:air-pollution/2009-southeast-asian-haze] With a prevailing dry season caused by El Nino, burning and hence the haze was expected to continue until August or September when the monsoon season arrived.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:air-pollution/air-pollution] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
